Preheat the #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

In a large #bowl{}, combine the @Irish Pork Mince{240%g}, @breadcrumbs{1%pack}, 2 tbsp @water{2%tbsp} and @salt{1/4%tsp}.

Season with @pepper{to taste} and mix together by hand.

Roll into evenly-sized balls, 3-4 per person.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Pop the meatballs onto a lined #baking tray{}.

When the oven is hot, bake on the top shelf until browned on the outside and cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Meatballs are cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Pour the @couscous{100%g} and half the @chicken stock{1%sachet} into a bowl.

Stir in @boiling water{200%ml}.

Cover with a #plate{} or #cling film{}.

Leave aside for ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{75%g} and then chop into thirds. Halve the @cherry tomatoes{125%g}.

Halve, peel and chop the @shallot{1}(halved, peeled and chopped) into small pieces.

Roughly chop the @parsley{5%g}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Place a pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, add the green beans, cherry tomatoes and shallot.

Fry until starting to char, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in the @ras-el-hanout{1%sachet} and fry for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @passata{1%pack}, @sugar{1/2%tsp}, 2 tbsp @water{2%tbsp}, remaining stock and cooked meatballs.

Cover and simmer until the veg is tender, ~{4-5%minutes}.

To finish, mix through the @harissa paste{1%sachet}, @honey{1%sachet} and a knob of @butter{to taste}.

Add a splash of @water{to taste} to loosen the sauce if you feel it's too thick. Taste and season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> TIP: Add less harissa if you don't like things spicy!

Mix half the parsley into the couscous, fluffing it up as you go.

Divide the herby couscous between deep #plates{} or #bowls{}.

Top with the meatballs and veg, drizzling over any sauce remaining in the pan.

Finish with a scattering of the remaining chopped parsley.